=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=faramir42>Faramir42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/27/03 2:55 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: old times it was easier ?</span><hr size=1> I wouldn't say wizards are broken. I would say that they have been ignored by the Developement teams. For the longest time, Mages complained about how weak they were, how thier pets never listened and that all they were good at was summoning stuff. So Sony made some changes to the pets, tossed a few nukes, now everyone loves mages. Sony even said the class was under powered, and that they had always intended for mages to be good damage dealers. Fair enough. Nothing against Mages, I enjoy grouping with them. Yes, it is a bit annoying to think that Sony just gives them a buyable nuke as good as one of ours. I can live with it. <br>
<br>
There are lots of mage only items out there. Some are rather recent. These were put into the game to encourage people to play mages again. I do think Sony went farther then they needed to make mages balanced at the same level with other classes. I can live with that. <br>
<br>
At level 52, I'm at 241 int, and as best as I can figure out, I'm at 2700 mana with my equipment. I believe the mana cap for casters is just over 4000k at level 60. So I'm not that far off. I have an earring of soltice, my familar up, and manaskin, in effect, giving me a three point mana regen per tick at all times over normal regen. Not bad really. I have a horse, so I can sit on him when outdoors. The mana just flies up then.<br>
<br>
Yes, I think it's a shame that none of our nukes get to the 3k mark, even at 65. I can live with that. One thing we have over other casters is that some of our spells are harder to resist. Which means we are going to do damage, while mages are wasting mana trying to land a nuke and kept thier pet alive. We have all kinds of damage spells. Fire, cold and magic. Posion and disease based spells would be interesting too, but oh well. Mages are lucky, they get Malo, which allows them to lower resistances before nuking. What would be nice is some lower damage nukes, like Ro's Sundering for druids, that would lower resistances at the same time. But we don't.<br>
<br>
I was told that wizards have the best chance of getting a Crit then other caster classes. I don't know if this is true or not. I do know I crit more then other casters around me.<br>
<br>
I do think wizards are a bit limited in their range of spells. Mages have nukes, utilites and buffs. Same for necros and enchanters. Personally, I like not having to buff 5 or more people. So I really wouldn't want a range of buffs for others. Though a few for ourselves would be nice. Why don't we have better damage shields? Aren't we the masters of damage in all it's forms? <br>
<br>
Why not give us an interesting line of shield spells? What if, instead of just minor ac, hp and mr increases, they had different effects? Say the first one had an effect like a shadowstep spell? each time you're hit, poof, you port away. What if one had a stun on it? You get hit, the mob is stunned. None of these shields need be long lasting or unresistable, in the case of the stun idea. What about an aggro lowering shield? Get hit, the aggro lowers, and the mob turns onto someone else, providing there is someone else. A shield that we get hit, the mob is rooted for a tick and we can move away? These shields could be non stackable, so someone couldnt' have a stun and aggro shield up at the same time. They might not even be stackable with the regular line of shields. I only suggewst this, since mages, necros and enchanters all get some form of pet that also doubles as an HP buffer. Generally speaking, a mob has to go through the pet before getting to the caster. So a new line of shield spells wouldn't give us more HP's or AC. But it would be something different, on level with pets. That is like having a 3k hp buffer. More actually, since they can heal their pets. Basically, it working some of our spells into shields.<br>
<br>
The shadowstep spells should be reworked. Does anyone use them? First, they should have some aggro lowering effect on them. Like, if you get jumped, you cast the spell, and move away, lowering your aggro, the mob forgets about you and you run away. But if your fighting a mob, and think, oh this isn't going well, and cast it, it may not be enough to get the mob off you. They should also be less random in distance. The range of the best one still has a chance of porting you very little distance. They would be more popular if they ported you in just one direction, say the one you are facing. But they plop you down anywhere. <br>
<br>
I have always thought the call of the hero spell was misplaced as a mage spell. They are good at summoning items, but moving people around is a wizard job (I don't included druids, because I am thinking of Translocates over porting). Why can't we have a spell that summons a person to their corpse? Sort of like a rez, only they have to be grouped with the wizard, and there is no xp cost restored, and lets say the spell has a terrible high cost gem. That way, it wouldn't be considered like a rez, or a summon corpse. <br>
<br>
Many of the wizard port spell have been made useless since PoP came out. Commons, Nek or N Ro were great to getting to Freeport. Now, you can get right to Freeport. The leve 54 levitate spell, also, no good, as O'Kiels Levity not only gives you an hour of levitation, but Fire resistance, and damage shield and Infravision with no component cost. Why would I care about an NPC (now researchable) drop spell that costs no batwing and lasts ten minutes and is self only? Maybe if they changed this spell to a buff that can be cast on others. Not all our spells are stackable with other buffs. Our shield spells don't stack with shaman spells. Since ours are self only, how is it going to hurt if they did? <br>
<br>
Our nukes are fine. In the end, they do more damage then anyone elses. Mages included. I hear lots of people at 50 wishing they get a nuke that did 600 - 1k damage, and we have that at 49. Tears of Druzzil spell is great. I've used it in Plane of Inovation many times. More often then not, all three waves land. That's 1800 damage for 380. Mages can't do that till 55. I was grouped with 2 level 55 mages once in POI, we decided to cast our spells all at the same time. That was three waves of 1800 damage each. The mobs fell so fast, you wouldn't believe it.<br>
<br>
Our roots could use some reworking. They are all the same, save that each one has the POTENTIAL to last longer. Rooted mobs have a chance to break each tick (six seconds) or every time it takes damage. Fair enough, a chance keeps it interesting. And the higher you are the lower the mobs chance are. Well, the duration it gets to check should also change as they get better. Root should be every tick, enstill, every 2 ticks (12 seconds) and immobolize every 3 ticks and so on. That would make a root like Paraylizing earth a very nice uselful root. What about an AE root? A Point Blank AE root for when you get mobbed? That would be nice. The duration could be very short for these types of spells. Making them more for escaping then kitting. Unlike AE stuns, the mobs can still hit you if rooted and you are still close. It would also be nice if our one snare wouldn't effect us. Since it doesn't effect other players, why does it effect us? A single target snare wouldn't be out of line. <br>
<br>
The Elnricks Entombment was a nice spell idea, but I quickly realized, it wasn't that good of a spell. Wizards are supposed to also be masters of instant movement. There are lots of ideas that can be used for this. What about a spell that will port a mob back to it's spawn point? Or at least move him farther away from you? We have a few spells that knock back creatures. Why not a knock back and root version? Or at least make the knock back farther then what it is. I've used the knockback spell on Kael raids to help move the mob up againts the walls so we could pin it into position while the tank and the giant went at it head to toe, so to speak.<br>
<br>
Give us better or longer lasting eye spells. Yes, they did change them so they didn't get aggro. Good. Now make them last longer then a few seconds. I've never a use for bind sight other then having some fun. I've tried using to to jump from mob to mob, to get an idea of how many creatures could be in a room, but often they mob isn't looking in the right direction. The best use I have found for this is guiding lost members through areas by seeing through thier eyes. But with all the old zones mapped out, anyone can find thier way around with eaze.<br>
<br>
It seems to me, that the dev teams have tried experimenting with various ideas for wizard spells, but were afraid to give them to much power or go into area's that belonged to other casters. At the same time, so many of our spells go unused. I hardly ever cast the heat sight or chill sight spells, as in time, I had items that acted as a light source. I do use the vision increasing spells from time to time. Each time they come out with a new spell, it seems to replace one we already had. (O'Kiels/Levitate at 54). So we really aren't getting new spells, just some better ones. <br>
<br>
I still enjoy playing a wizard. And I play a good one. I seldom slow down a group with OOM, as I don't think it's my job to burn down the mob completly. I assume my job is to do my share of damage, based on how many damage dealers there are in the group. 3 melees, a cleric, an enchanter and me, then my share of damage is about one quater.  <br>
<br>
If someone has trouble finding a group all the time, as a wizard, all I think is that they spent so much time soloing, they haven't made very many firends. I can always tell when someone has had a soloing career, from the way they play. I have lots of friends and can always find a group, or start making my own group. <br>
<br>
I get asked to join groups alot, from strangers, looking for a damage dealer. I get compliments from people I group with the first time about how nice it is to meet a wizard that doesn't get aggro all the time, and the same time I'm nuking enough to make a big difference. My friends say the notice a difference when I'm not arround in how long it takes to bring down a mob. <br>
<br>
